"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994193","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-01","<p>I attended the Sir Bani Yas Forum in the United Arab Emirates in November 2017 in my capacity as Minister for the Middle East and North Africa.​</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-11-01T16:26:47.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994193/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994193/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994193/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-24","United Arab Emirates: Official Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the trip to the United Arab Emirates taken by the hon. Member for North East Bedfordshire in November 2017 was taken in his official ministerial capacity.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","183261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994194","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-11-01","<p>The Government is making progress and remains confident of ensuring a functioning statute book as we leave the EU. All statutory instruments are being published on legislation.gov.uk, and can also be found on Parliament’s tracker at <a href="https://beta.parliament.uk/find-a-statutory-instrument" target="_blank">https://beta.parliament.uk/find-a-statutory-instrument</a>. The Government has committed that statutory instruments relating to EU exit will be clearly titled.</p>","Fareham","Suella Braverman",,"2018-11-01T16:49:52.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994194/answer","Biography information for Suella Braverman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994194/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994194/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-10-24","Statutory Instruments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to the Hansard Society article Westminster Lens: Brexit Statutory Instruments Dashboard, published on 22 October 2018,  what progress the Government has made on the outstanding statutory instruments to prepare the statute book for the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","183448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994195","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-01","<p>I was accompanied by one official on my visit to the United Arab Emirates in November 2017.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-11-01T16:28:54.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994195/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994195/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994195/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-24","United Arab Emirates: Official Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether civil servants accompanied the Minister of State for the Middle East on his visit to the UAE in November 2017.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","183262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994196","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-29","<p>The information requested is not centrally held.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-10-29T17:45:35.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994196/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994196/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994196/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-24","Diabetes: East Ham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many East Ham residents have accessed the NHS diabetes prevention programme in each year since it was established.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","183224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994197","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-10-29","<p>It has not been possible to provide an analysis of the figures at constituency level. The figures provided below are for the boroughs of Southwark and Lambeth, part of which fall within the Dulwich and Norwood constituency. Our monitoring and statistics show that 75% of appeals scheduled for a final hearing do settle or concede prior to the hearing date with a decision at hearing not required.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Appeals Made</p></td><td><p>Southwark</p></td><td><p>Lambeth</p></td><td><p>TOTAL</p></td><td><p>LONDON</p></td><td><p>NATIONAL</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014 – 15</p></td><td><p>26</p></td><td><p>51</p></td><td><p>77</p></td><td><p>784</p></td><td><p>3147</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 – 16</p></td><td><p>26</p></td><td><p>35</p></td><td><p>61</p></td><td><p>791</p></td><td><p>3712</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016 – 17</p></td><td><p>44</p></td><td><p>32</p></td><td><p>76</p></td><td><p>823</p></td><td><p>4725</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017 - 18 (*)</p></td><td><p>76</p></td><td><p>37</p></td><td><p>113</p></td><td><p>1131</p></td><td><p>5679</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Disposed (**)</p></td><td><p>SOUTHWARK<br> Decided</p></td><td><p>SOUTHWARK<br> In Favour of Appellant</p></td><td><p>SOUTHWARK<br> Decisions Upheld</p></td><td><p>LAMBETH<br> Decided</p></td><td><p>LAMBETH<br> In Favour of Appellant</p></td><td><p>LAMBETH<br> Decisions Upheld</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014 - 15</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>31</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 - 16</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016 - 17</p></td><td><p>26</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017 - 18</p></td><td><p>32</p></td><td><p>31</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>18</p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>LONDON<br> Appeals Decided</p></td><td><p>LONDON<br> In favour of Appellant (***)</p></td><td><p>LONDON<br> Decisions upheld</p></td><td><p>National<br> Appeals Decided</p></td><td><p>National<br> In favour of Appellant (***)</p></td><td><p>National<br> Decisions upheld</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>288</p></td><td><p>252</p></td><td><p>36</p></td><td><p>788</p></td><td><p>680</p></td><td><p>108</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>301</p></td><td><p>270</p></td><td><p>31</p></td><td><p>883</p></td><td><p>780</p></td><td><p>103</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>385</p></td><td><p>343</p></td><td><p>42</p></td><td><p>1599</p></td><td><p>1418</p></td><td><p>181</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>407</p></td><td><p>359</p></td><td><p>48</p></td><td><p>2298</p></td><td><p>2035</p></td><td><p>263</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>* - 2017 - 18 figures have not yet been published and are currently being analysed and verified ready for publication on 13 December 2018 as part of the Special Educational Needs and Disability (SEND) Tribunals annual statistics</p><p><br> ** - Appeals disposed are within the same time period. In SEND the Tribunal hears appeals within 22 weeks of the appeal registered. Therefore, figures may be different from those registered in the period as those hearings could follow into the next reporting year.</p><p><br> *** - The Tribunal reports a successful appeal if one part or all of the appeal is found in favour of the parent or young person. HMCTS manual data collections show that 75% of appeals scheduled for a final hearing do settle or concede prior to the hearing date with a decision at hearing not required.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-10-29T15:17:52.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994197/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994197/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994197/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-10-24","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate his Department has made of the number of appeals made to the special educational needs and disability tribunal in each year since 2014; and of those appeals, how many have found against local authorities in (a) Dulwich and West Norwood, (b) London and (c) England.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","183449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994198","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-29","<p>Reducing amputations by improving access to Multi-Disciplinary Footcare Teams (MDFT) for people with diabetic foot disease is one of four areas that NHS England’s diabetes management and care programme is focusing on.</p><p> </p><p>£9.6 million has been invested to reduce amputations in people with diabetes through new/expanded MDFTs in approximately 80 hospital sites, funding approximately 185 whole time equivalent additional staff.</p><p> </p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-10-29T17:47:06.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994198/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994198/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994198/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-24","Diabetes: Podiatry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what plans his Department has to maintain investment in multi-disciplinary foot care teams as part of the diabetes programme in the NHS ten year plan.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","183225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994199","Department for International Development","false","2018-10-30","<p>DFID’s bilateral spending on human development remained the same between 2016/17 and 2017/18 at £1.9bn. Bilateral spending on economic development rose from £1.7bn in 2016/17 to £1.9bn in 2017/18. The data are available on the International Aid Transparency Initiative (IATI) website.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-10-30T15:04:32.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994199/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994199/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994199/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-10-24","Bilateral Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, for what reason her Department's bilateral aid spending on (a) human development and (b) economic development declined in financial year 2017-18 compared with 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","183450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994200","Department for Education","false","2018-10-29","<p>Nationally, the Teachers’ Pay Grant of £508 million covers the difference between the 1% pay award schools would have been planning for under the previous public sector pay cap and the average of the 2018 pay award.</p><p> </p><p>At a school level, the Government is using a per-pupil formula to allocate the funding, to ensure simplicity and timeliness in getting money to schools. Not every school has the same staffing structure, and so the grant will not exactly match their costs in every case.</p><p> </p><p>Officials met with a number of stakeholder groups to discuss the methodology of the grant, and took account of the views expressed in determining its final structure.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","183455","2018-10-29T17:13:21.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994200/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994200/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994200/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-24","Teachers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Written Statement of 24 October 2018 on Teachers' Pay Grant, Official Report HCWS1028, for what reason his Department decided to use pupil numbers as the basis for distributing the grant; and what consultation his Department undertook on that issue.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","183451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994201","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-29","<p>This was not an official report by the Infrastructure and Projects Authority. The document represented an individual’s personal views. We do not comment on leaks.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-10-29T16:33:20.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994201/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994201/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994201/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-24","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, for what reason the Government will not make available to MPs the 2017 Infrastructure Projects Authority report which assessed the cost of High Speed Two at £80 billion; and with what part of that report's methodology for assessing the costs of that project the Department disagrees.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","183235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994202","Home Office","false","2018-10-29","<p>The Government has decided not to opt in to the EU’s “e-evidence” Regulation as while we share the EU’s objectives in this area, it is not clear that the Regulation will be a practical or effective way to address what is a global issue. This opt in decision will have no impact on how UK law enforcement carry out international and domestic criminal investigations.</p><p>We are also legislating domestically to tackle this issue, through the Crime (Overseas Production Orders) Bill. This legislation will allow law enforcement agencies and prosecutors to apply directly to service providers based in a territory with whom the UK has a relevant international agreement, by way of a UK court approved order for stored electronic data. This will make the process for gaining access to this type of data faster.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-10-29T17:11:35.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994202/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994202/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994202/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-24","Evidence: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment he has made of effect on the (a) cost and (b) duration of international and domestic criminal investigations of the decision not to opt-in to the Proposal of the European Parliament and the Council on European Production Orders and European Preservation Orders for cross-border access to electronic evidence on criminal matters.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","183452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994203","Treasury","false","2018-11-01","<p>While we remain confident that we will secure a positive and mutually beneficial deal with the EU, there remain a number of border-related projects that have to be delivered in the unlikely event of no deal being agreed. Some of these projects were initiated before the UK decided to leave and so are not exclusively EU exit related.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested is not held centrally, however, the 12 border-related projects listed in the NAO report are all at different stages of development with a number part of wider programmes. As such, it would not be possible to attach a single overarching cost at this time.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-11-01T17:31:52.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994203/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994203/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994203/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-24","Borders: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the total cost will be of developing the 12 critical IT systems required at the border after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","183263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994204","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-29","<p>The information is not available in the format requested.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-10-29T17:24:53.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994204/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994204/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994204/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-24","Orthopaedics: Newham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many (a) major and (b) minor amputations have been carried out on residents of the London borough of Newham since 2014; and how those numbers compare with the national average.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","183226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994205","Home Office","false","2018-11-01","<p>The exact number of contingent labour staff within the Programme varies dependent on the specific expertise required during the lifecycle of the Programme. Contingent Labour staff are used to provide specific, time-limited expertise, from a pool of specialists offering skills that the Civil Service can draw from when and as needed, rather than employing these specialists on a permanent basis including during periods when their skills are not needed.</p><p>As at the 25<sup>th</sup> October 2018, DSAB had engaged under contract a total of 20 contingent labour contractors.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-11-01T16:37:57.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994205/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994205/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994205/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-24","Borders: Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people working on the Digital Services at the Border programme are classed as contingent labour.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","183264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994206","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-01","<p>Following an initial meeting with a cross section of stakeholders in May, the Cabinet Office has been working with the Department of Health and Social Care, the Department for Education and a range of other organisations to consider next steps in this area. We are pleased to support the launch of a new University Mental Health Charter in June 2018, aiming to drive up standards in promoting student and staff mental health and wellbeing. Universities will be awarded a new recognition for meeting improved standards.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-11-01T16:54:28.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994206/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994206/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994206/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-24","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the Green Paper on Transforming Children and Young People’s Mental Health Provision, what steps he is taking to implement the national strategic partnership on mental health for 16 to 25-year-olds.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","183453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994207","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-01","<p>Voluntary conversion to a different religion is not a criminal offence in India. However, laws are active in six of India's 29 states that seek to prevent 'forced' conversion and make the legal process altogether more difficult.</p><p> </p><p>On freedom of religion more broadly, the British High Commission in New Delhi and our network of Deputy High Commissions regularly meet with minority communities, including the National Commission of Minority Affairs. Additionally we have trained nine hundred minority students on faith issues in six universities across North India, and funded a community cohesion project which created a platform for 125 youth champions drawn from 26 colleges. This engaged with diverse religious communities through a series of workshops to initiate change, within themselves, their peers, and family as well as encouraging greater dialogue and understanding across communities.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-11-01T16:10:26.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994207/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994207/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994207/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-24","India: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the implications for freedom of religion in India of the recent action by Indian authorities against religious groups as a result of anti-conversion laws; and whether he has made representations to his Indian counterpart on that issue.","false","Biography information for Steve Double","St Austell and Newquay","Steve Double","183454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994208","Home Office","false","2018-11-01","<p>The Government Digital Service and the Home Office meet regularly, including planned and ad hoc meetings. The Home Office is also a member of two forums managed by GDS: the Technology and Digital Leaders Group and the Functional Leaders Group.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-11-01T16:35:50.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994208/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994208/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994208/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-24","Home Office: Government Digital Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many meetings Home Office Digital, Data and Technology has had with the Government Digital Service in the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","183265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994209","Department for Education","false","2018-10-29","<p>Nationally, the Teachers’ Pay Grant of £508 million covers the difference between the 1% pay award schools would have been planning for under the previous public sector pay cap and the average of the 2018 pay award.</p><p> </p><p>At a school level, the Government is using a per-pupil formula to allocate the funding, to ensure simplicity and timeliness in getting money to schools. Not every school has the same staffing structure, and so the grant will not exactly match their costs in every case.</p><p> </p><p>Officials met with a number of stakeholder groups to discuss the methodology of the grant, and took account of the views expressed in determining its final structure.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","183451","2018-10-29T17:13:21.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994209/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994209/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994209/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-24","Teachers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, further to the Written Statement of 24 October 2018 on Teachers' Pay Grant, Official Report HCWS1028, what estimate he has made of the number of schools that (a) will and (b) will not have the full cost of the increase in teachers' pay above the first 1 per cent of the rise covered by that grant.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","183455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994210","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-01","<p>The Five Year Forward View for Mental Health is at the heart of Government plans to transform mental health services and recognises early intervention as key to improving service user experiences and preventing the requirement for in-patient stays. Page 15 of the Five Year Forward View notes that:</p><p> </p><p>“Early intervention and quick access to good quality care is vital – especially for children and young people. Waiting times should be substantially reduced, significant inequalities in access should be addressed and support should be offered while people are waiting for care.”</p><p>Following publication of the Five Year Forward View, and in recognition of the value of early intervention, the Government agreed the following waiting times and access targets with NHS England.</p><p>- For accessing Improving Access to Psychological Therapies services 75% of referrals should be seen within six weeks and 95% should be seen within 18 weeks;</p><p>- For eating disorder services 95% of referrals should be seen within four weeks for routine cases and 95% of urgent referrals should be seen within one week; and</p><p>- For the Early Intervention in Psychosis programme 50% of people experiencing a first episode of psychosis should start a National Institute for Health and Care Excellence recommended package of care within two weeks of referral, rising to 60% by 2021.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-11-01T16:44:36.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994210/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994210/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994210/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-24","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the effect of early intervention by mental health services on people with mental health issues.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","183456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994211","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-01","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) it has recently set up a commercial function that specifically focuses on engaging in discussions around commercial arrangements - The Commercial and Managed Access Programme. Through this function, NICE will provide companies with opportunities to engage in commercial and managed access conversations with both NICE and NHS England.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-11-01T16:46:48.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994211/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994211/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994211/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-24","Medical Treatments: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what plans the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence has to facilitate commercial discussions between manufacturers and NHS England at an early stage in its evaluations of highly specialised technologies.","false","Biography information for Jared O'Mara","Sheffield, Hallam","Jared O'Mara","183457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994212","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-01","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) evaluates all medicines referred to its highly specialised technologies (HST) programme, including medicines for Duchenne muscular dystrophy, consistently in accordance with its published methods and processes. In 2017, following public consultation, NICE introduced an assessment of cost-effectiveness into its HST methodology that provides a consistent and transparent mechanism for evaluating technologies while recognising the need for greater flexibility in the evaluation of very high cost drugs for the treatment of very rare diseases.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-11-01T16:39:13.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994212/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994212/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994212/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-24","Muscular Dystrophy: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the introduction of a cost-effectiveness threshold in the NICE highly specialised technologies appraisal process, what steps he is taking to ensure equity of access to treatment for different subgroups of patients with Duchenne muscular dystrophy.","false","Biography information for Jared O'Mara","Sheffield, Hallam","Jared O'Mara","183458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994213","Department for Education","false","2018-10-29","<p>The information requested is shown in the table in Annex A, which is attached.</p><p> </p><p>With regard to workforce costs, the first year set-up and running costs for the National Schools Commissioner (NSC), Regional Schools Commissioners (RSCs) and their teams for the financial year 2014-15 was £4.1 million. This was funded from existing departmental resources.</p><p> </p><p>Many of the duties carried out in RSC offices were previously handled by local authorities.</p><p> </p><p>As a result of structural changes within the department in 2016-17, the Academies Regional Delivery Group (ARDG) was created. This incorporated the NSC and RSCs with complementary regional functions and other functions. Workforce costs for ARDG are therefore not comparable with predecessor structures and organisation.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","183460","2018-10-29T17:42:13.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994213/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994213/answer","183459_183460_Annex_A.pdf","183459_183460_Annex_A","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994213/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-24","Regional Schools Commissioner and Schools Commissioner","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the running costs have been of the (a) National Schools Commissioner and (b) Regional Schools Commissioners in each fiscal year since 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","183459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994214","Department for Education","false","2018-10-29","<p>The information requested is shown in the table in Annex A, which is attached.</p><p> </p><p>With regard to workforce costs, the first year set-up and running costs for the National Schools Commissioner (NSC), Regional Schools Commissioners (RSCs) and their teams for the financial year 2014-15 was £4.1 million. This was funded from existing departmental resources.</p><p> </p><p>Many of the duties carried out in RSC offices were previously handled by local authorities.</p><p> </p><p>As a result of structural changes within the department in 2016-17, the Academies Regional Delivery Group (ARDG) was created. This incorporated the NSC and RSCs with complementary regional functions and other functions. Workforce costs for ARDG are therefore not comparable with predecessor structures and organisation.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","183459","2018-10-29T17:42:13.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994214/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994214/answer","183459_183460_Annex_A.pdf","183459_183460_Annex_A","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994214/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-24","Regional Schools Commissioner and Schools Commissioner","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many staff work under the (a) National Schools Commissioner and (b) Regional Schools Commissioners.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","183460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994215","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-01","<p>Officials from the British Embassy regularly attend court hearings of cases of interest to the UK. We will continue to monitor the cases of Mohamed Ramadan and Husain Ali Moosa closely.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-11-01T16:30:13.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994215/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994215/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994215/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-24","Bahrain: Political Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will ensure that there is a UK Government trial monitoring presence at each hearing of the retrial of Mohamed Ramadhan and Husain Moosa in Bahrain.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","183309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994216","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-29","<p>The Children’s Hospice Grant is awarded annually and administered by NHS England. It is a contribution towards the operating costs of the hospices, not core funding for NHS services, for which the statutory responsibility resides with local commissioners. In 2018/19 £11 million has been provided to children’s hospices through the Grant.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-10-29T15:56:56.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994216/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994216/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994216/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-24","Hospices: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will increase the annual level of ringfenced funding that children’s hospices receive from NHS England to £25 million to reflect the changing number of seriously ill children whom they are caring for.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","183299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994217","Department for Education","false","2018-10-30","<p>For 2019-20, the Department estimates that £1.1 billion more will need to be put into the Teachers’ Pension Scheme by employers to ensure teachers’ pensions remain generous and attractive to the profession. This is broken down as down as follows: £830 million from state-funded schools, £110 million from the Independent Sector, £80 million from Further Education Colleges and £80 million from affected Higher Education Institutions.</p><p> </p><p>It is the Government’s intention to fund independent special schools for the costs of increased employer contributions in 2019-20, as these schools often have pupils on education, health and care plans, which are local authority funded, but the Department will be consulting to seek views on this to understand the impact these costs will impose on the independent schools sector.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","183462","2018-10-30T13:40:48.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994217/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994217/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994217/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994217/answer/previousversion/81657","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994217/answer/previousversion/81657",,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-24","Teachers: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 18 October 2018 to Question 179233, what estimate he has made of the cost to employers other than state-funded schools of increasing the employer contribution to the Teachers' Pension Scheme.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","183461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994218","Department for Education","false","2018-10-30","<p>For 2019-20, the Department estimates that £1.1 billion more will need to be put into the Teachers’ Pension Scheme by employers to ensure teachers’ pensions remain generous and attractive to the profession. This is broken down as down as follows: £830 million from state-funded schools, £110 million from the Independent Sector, £80 million from Further Education Colleges and £80 million from affected Higher Education Institutions.</p><p> </p><p>It is the Government’s intention to fund independent special schools for the costs of increased employer contributions in 2019-20, as these schools often have pupils on education, health and care plans, which are local authority funded, but the Department will be consulting to seek views on this to understand the impact these costs will impose on the independent schools sector.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","183461","2018-10-30T13:40:48.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994218/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994218/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994218/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994218/answer/previousversion/81658","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994218/answer/previousversion/81658",,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-24","Teachers: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 18 October 2018 to Question 179233, whether he plans to provide funding to for-profit providers of independent special schools to meet their increased employer contributions to the Teachers' Pension Scheme.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","183462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994219","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-01","<p>DfT is working together with the Rail Industry to enable facility for Automatic Power Change Over (APCO) on Intercity Express Trains on the East Coast and Great Western routes. This includes appropriate power change over arrangements at Steventon Bridge. I understand that Network Rail have launched a formal appeal to the Planning Inspectorate against the local authority decision to refuse planning permission for replacing Steventon Bridge.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-11-01T16:15:31.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994219/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994219/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994219/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-24","Railway Signals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 19 October 2018 to Question 178321, what assessment he has made of the role of his Department in overseeing the introduction of the Automatic Power Change Over (APCO) system integration (a) across the InterCity Express programme and (b) at the Signalling Scheme Plan at Steventon Bridge.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","183463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994220","Department for International Development","false","2018-10-31","<p>The Secretary of State has corresponded with the Minister of State for Employment on the proposed Convention on Ending Violence and Harassment in the World of Work. They have agreed that officials and legal advisers at the Government Equalities Office and the Department for International Development will work in close partnership with the Department for Work and Pensions to help deliver a successful outcome for the UK on this important issue.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-10-31T17:46:21.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994220/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994220/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994220/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-10-24","Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions on UK support for the proposed ILO convention on ending violence and harassment in the workplace.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","183318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994221","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-01","<p>I refer the hon Member to the written Answer I gave on 13 September to Question 170780 on the Rail Delivery Group (RDG) which sets out the RDG’s role in rail industrial relations.</p><p> </p><p>Ultimately, the day to day responsibility for managing industrial relations or any dispute in the rail sector will be a matter for the individual employers and trade unions.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-11-01T16:31:12.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994221/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994221/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994221/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-24","Railways: Industrial Disputes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 19 October 2018 to Question 178322 on Train Operating Companies: Pay, what (a) locus, (b) authority or (c) remit the Rail Delivery Group has to intervene in rail industry industrial relations.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","183464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994222","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-01","<p>The Government supports the adoption of an ILO Convention on ending violence and harassment in the world of work. The Government is fully engaged in discussions in the ILO on the scope and content of the proposed Convention and as part of that is in regular contact with other states on this issue. The text of the Convention under negotiation includes informal workers and, if universally ratified, would apply to the world’s poorest workers. The Government’s position on the definitions and scope of the Convention is that it should provide broad coverage, whilst being ratifiable by as large a number of the ILO’s membership as possible.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","183320 ; 183322 ; 183969","2018-11-01T16:04:02.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994222/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994222/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994222/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-24","Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans she has to ensure that the proposed June 2019 ILO Convention includes (a) informal workers and (b) the world’s other poorest workers.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","183319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994223","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-01","<p>The Government supports the adoption of an ILO Convention on ending violence and harassment in the world of work. The Government is fully engaged in discussions in the ILO on the scope and content of the proposed Convention and as part of that is in regular contact with other states on this issue. The text of the Convention under negotiation includes informal workers and, if universally ratified, would apply to the world’s poorest workers. The Government’s position on the definitions and scope of the Convention is that it should provide broad coverage, whilst being ratifiable by as large a number of the ILO’s membership as possible.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","183319 ; 183322 ; 183969","2018-11-01T16:04:02.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994223/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994223/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994223/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-24","Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the ILO Brown report on ending violence and harassment in the world of work, whether the Government supports the definitions in that report of (a) violence and harassment, (b) workplace and (c) worker.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","183320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994224","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-01","<p>To answer parts (a), (b) and (c) of the question, the DfT has worked with the rail industry to publish a Joint Rail Data Action Plan. This outlines the Government’s assessment on open and closed rail data, and sets out a number of actions the rail industry will take to ensure data is being shared and used for the benefit of the railways and rail passengers.</p><p> </p><p>This plan will ensure a shift in the railway industry’s approach to using and sharing its data, including new datasets to be made openly available, improvement on how data is collected and classified and new initiatives to bring the rail and technology sectors together. This will drive forward innovation within the rail industry and forge partnerships with the developer community so that the use of data is maximised and more accurate and up-to-date information is put into the hands of the passengers.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/joint-rail-data-action-plan" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/joint-rail-data-action-plan</a></p><p> </p><p>To answer part (d) of the question, the Office of Rail and Road (ORR) monitor data quality through the use of Independent Reporters as part of their role as the rail regulator. These provide assessments of data quality for Network Rail’s data. The metrics and datasets they assess are given a grading based on system reliability and data accuracy. These assessment reports are published on the ORR’s website.</p><p><a href="http://orr.gov.uk/rail/economic-regulation/regulation-of-network-rail/monitoring-performance/independent-reporters" target="_blank">http://orr.gov.uk/rail/economic-regulation/regulation-of-network-rail/monitoring-performance/independent-reporters</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-11-01T17:00:33.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994224/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994224/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994224/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-24","Train Operating Companies and Network Rail: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of (a) open and closed data, (b) data produced legacy systems, (c) data owned or created by train operating companies and (d) data from Network Rail.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","183465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994225","Department for International Development","false","2018-10-31","<p>DFID’s £30.3M Responsible Accountable Transparent Enterprise Programme (RATE) is focussed on promoting job quality standards in developing countries, including ending workplace violence and harassment. All of the organisations funded by this programme, including the Ethical Trading Initiative, ShareAction, Shift and World Benchmarking Alliance are active on this agenda.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-10-31T17:47:13.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994225/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994225/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994225/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-10-24","Developing Countries: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate she has made of the funding allocated by her Department to tackle workplace violence and harassment in developing countries; and which programmes that funding covers.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","183321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994226","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-01","<p>The Government supports the adoption of an ILO Convention on ending violence and harassment in the world of work. The Government is fully engaged in discussions in the ILO on the scope and content of the proposed Convention and as part of that is in regular contact with other states on this issue. The text of the Convention under negotiation includes informal workers and, if universally ratified, would apply to the world’s poorest workers. The Government’s position on the definitions and scope of the Convention is that it should provide broad coverage, whilst being ratifiable by as large a number of the ILO’s membership as possible.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","183319 ; 183320 ; 183969","2018-11-01T16:04:03.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994226/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994226/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994226/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-24","Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans she has to discuss the proposed June 2019 ILO Convention with (a) Governments of African countries and (b) other Governments.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","183322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994227","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-10-31","<p>We are committed to getting the best possible deal for the United Kingdom - a deal that works for all parts of the UK, including the North West. We do not want or expect a no-deal scenario and remain confident that we will secure a mutually advantageous deal with the EU. We continue to engage with businesses and industry bodies from all sectors of the economy, and all regions and nations of the UK, in order to inform our negotiations.<br><br>The Government is undertaking a wide range of ongoing analysis, across a range of scenarios, in support of our EU exit negotiations and preparations. Ministers have a specific responsibility, which Parliament has endorsed, not to release information that would reveal our negotiating position and so the Government will not provide an ongoing commentary on internal analytical work.</p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2018-10-31T14:31:00.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994227/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994227/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994227/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-10-24","Brexit: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on the North West of (a) the UK leaving the EU without a deal and (b) the EU accepting the Chequers proposals.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","183273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994228","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-01","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>I can confirm that the Department has not had any such meetings with either First Group or MTR.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-11-01T15:43:38.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994228/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994228/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994228/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-24","South Western Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what meetings his Department has held with (a) First Group and (b) MTR on renegotiating the South Western franchise.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","183466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994229","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-01","<p>All franchise payments between the Department and franchisee are commercially sensitive and therefore confidential.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-11-01T16:43:31.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994229/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994229/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994229/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-24","South Western Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the shortfall in revenues on the South Western rail franchise as a result of the December 2018 timetable not being introduced.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","183467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994230","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-01","<p>The timeframes for the new franchise are yet to be determined. It would be for an operator of the franchise to establish their specific rolling stock requirements.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-11-01T16:56:54.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994230/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994230/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994230/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-24","Cross Country Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the timeframe is for the procurement of new rolling stock on the Cross Country rail franchise.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","183468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994231","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-01","<p>The Secretary of State has set up the East Coast Partnership Board which brings together LNER and Network Rail along with representation for freight and other East Coast Main Line train operators (the Partnership) to collaborate on the planning of enhancements, ensuring improved coordination in delivery and greater passenger focus.</p><p> </p><p>The Partnership will jointly be able to take decisions about planning, maintenance and enhancement works alongside the interests of passengers to make sure that the two fit side by side.</p><p> </p><p>The evolution to the East Coast Partnership has already commenced allowing for deeper collaboration and joint working to improve performance and plan enhancements.</p><p> </p><p>Specifically, Network Rail has been instructed to deliver power supply upgrades between Doncaster and Edinburgh, a new rail junction near Peterborough, a new platform at Stevenage station and improvements to the track layout at King’s Cross. These enhancements will be completed in the early 2020s.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-11-01T16:25:05.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994231/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994231/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994231/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-24","London North Eastern Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what (a) instructions and (b) delivery timeframes he has issued to (i) LNER and (ii) Network Rail to develop the proposals for the LNER network.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","183469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994232","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-29","<p>Functional assessments are delivered on behalf of the Department by a range of suppliers.</p><p> </p><p>The Department requires Health Professionals to have broad training in disability analysis, as well as awareness training in specific conditions. These include autism.</p><p> </p><p>Health Professionals carrying out these functional assessments have access to training such as evidence based protocols, e-learning modules or case studies as well as keeping knowledge up to date through Continuous Professional Development. Health Professionals are not required to be an expert in a particular medical condition. They are expected to have a broad knowledge of different medical conditions and work with claimants to assess how these affect their daily life.</p><p> </p><p>DWP are committed to ensuring claimants receive high quality, objective and accurate assessments. We continue to work extensively with providers to make improvements to guidance and training in order to ensure the quality of the services are continuously improved.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-10-29T16:27:34.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994232/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994232/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/994232/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-24","Social Security Benefits: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 15 October 2018 to Question 177186 on Social Security Benefits: Appeals, what evidence-based protocol on autism healthcare professionals employed by his Department are required to learn as part of their training.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","183274"
